# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics Package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` (v2.0.1) as a project dependency
- Used npm to install the package
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency tree

### 2. Modified Root Layout (src/app/layout.tsx)
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag
- Positioned the Analytics component after the children content, following Vercel's official documentation

### 3. Files Modified
- **package.json** - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- **package-lock.json** - Updated with new package and its dependencies
- **src/app/layout.tsx** - Added Analytics import and component

## Implementation Details
The implementation follows the official Vercel Web Analytics quickstart guide for Next.js App Router:
- Fetched the latest documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
- Applied framework-specific instructions for Next.js App Router
- Maintained existing code structure and formatting
- Preserved all existing functionality

## Verification Steps Completed
✅ Successfully installed @vercel/analytics package
✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
✅ Linter passed with no issues
✅ TypeScript compilation successful
✅ All lock files updated appropriately

## Next Steps
To fully enable Vercel Web Analytics:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under the Analytics tab
3. Analytics will automatically start tracking page views and web vitals

## Notes
- The Analytics component is lightweight and won't impact performance
- No additional configuration is required for basic analytics tracking
- Analytics data will be visible in the Vercel dashboard after deployment
